sbol:Collection.dcterms:title: iGEM Parts Registry
sbol:Collection.dcterms:description: The iGEM Registry is a growing collection of genetic parts that can be mixed and matched to build synthetic biology devices and systems. As part of the synthetic biology community's efforts to make biology easier to engineer, it provides a source of genetic parts to iGEM teams and academic labs.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_M11319
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: These genes are involved in the D-olivose biosynthetic pathway. There is also a glycosyltransferase gene in this part.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: David Peterson
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: The promoter and ribosome binding sites came from biobrick parts. The sugar genes were converted into biobricks using PCR from the plasmid pLNR. THe glycosyltransferase urdGT2 came from streptomyces genomic DNA.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: These genes are for streptomyces to use when synthesizing new compounds.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_M11300
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: This is a glycosyltransferase used in the urdamycin biosynthetic pathway.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Amanda Romero

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_B0010
